decisions.title: Single Page Application only supports Chrome
decisions.content:
## Context
Single Page Application uses screensharing, WebRTC and AVC platform website scripts (clients), it is displayed in browser and inside Electron desktop application.
In previous versions of Chrome screensharing required a special browser extension ([sococo-screenshare](https://chrome.google.com/webstore/detail/sococo-screenshare/enfpclpejmdolpcgngfcilmjcekiklpo)), but currently screensharing has been made available to all web pages in the browser. The extension was easy to build and use, it had only several lines of code - to expose internal browser API to the page.
Google was developing their own communications platform (Hangouts) and invested into this technology stack and at the time this decision was made, WebRTC and screensharing only worked instantly in Chrome while other browsers required plugins, extensions, etc. Support for various operating systems was sparse and didn't always work. WebRTC support in different browsers was sparse, especially for transition from Internet Explorer to Edge.

## Decision
Use Chrome and Chromium as the only browser in which Sococo Single Page Application runs.

## Consequences
Users can't run Sococo Single Page Application in anything other than Chrome/Chromium.
The app displays "Sorry, your browser is not compatible." screen with suggestions to download desktop app for Mac/Windows/Linux or download Google Chrome.

decisions.title: Sococo AVC is an in-house backup AVC system
decisions.content:
## Context
Sococo platform requires a audio-video conferencing (AVC) solution to perform it's primary functions. External AVC systems like `Vidyo.io` or `Zoom` can have downtime.

## Decision
An in-house AVC system is built from open-source software like freeswitch, Jitsi (XMPP) and external VoIP provider (name?). The in-house AVC system built on open-source software is not as scalable as external systems (because it's based on fixed infrastructure and IaC concept is not set up for it), but can be used for back-up. 

## Consequences
- When primary AVC is experiencing an outage, all users can be temporarily switched to backup AVC.
- Users can be configured to work with in-house AVC permanently using administrator-level configuration panel.

decisions.title: Deploy Single Page Application container build onto CDN
decisions.content:
## Context
Single Page Application is written in Angular and supports webpack builds. Currently the application is served by RocketShorts server. It can and should be deployed as a webpack build onto a CDN to become an isolated container. This will greatly improve loading speed and will reduce the amount of servers, will allow RocketShorts to be deployed as microservices and will separate concerns for CI/CD.
